On Sunday, Macedonian citizens voted in a referendum to change their country's name to the "Republic of North Macedonia", a change that would settle a decade-old dispute with Greece, which opposed its accession to the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which comprises a province called Macedonia, argues that the name of the neighboring country represents a claim on its territory and has opposed its accession to the EU and NATO.
The two governments agreed in June on the proposed new name, but opposing nationalists argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of Macedonia's majority Slavic population.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum and that a boycott campaign has cast doubt on voter turnout, possibly not reaching the 50% threshold required to validate the referendum.
The question on the ballot in the referendum will be: “Do you agree to EU and NATO membership by accepting the agreement with Greece?”.
Proponents of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, say it is a price to be paid by Macedonia, one of the countries that resulted from the breakup of Yugoslavia, in order to be accepted into entities such as the EU and NATO.
“I am here today to vote for the future of the country, so that young people in Macedonia can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, because that means safer lives for all of us,” said 79-year-old Olivera Georgijevska in Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, quite a few members of parliament have said they will respect the outcome of the vote to make it decisive.
For the name to be changed, a two-thirds quorum in parliament is required.
The state electoral commission said no irregularities were reported until 13:00.
However, the turnout was only 16%, compared to 34% in the last parliamentary elections in 2016 when 66% of people with voting rights turned out to vote.
