“We support NATO and the EU, but we want to join them with our foreheads up, not through the back door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If we are not wanted by the name of Macedonia, we can go to other countries, such as China and Russia, and we can become part of the Eurasian Union.”
Prime Minister Zaev said NATO membership would bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20 percent.
“I think the majority will be in favor of changing the name, because more than 80% of our citizens are in favor of joining NATO and the EU,” Zaev said after voting.
He said one result in favor of changing the name would be “confirming our future.”
According to a poll published last Monday by the Policy Research Institute, between 30% and 43% of citizens with the right to vote will participate in the referendum, under the necessary number of participants.
According to another poll conducted by Telma TV in Macedonia, 57% of respondents plan to vote on Sunday.
Of those, 70 percent said they would vote for change.
In order for the referendum to be valid, the voter turnout must be 50% plus one vote.
