The higher judicial stamp duty will be applied to natural and legal persons who are not paying taxes in the United Kingdom, and the additional money obtained in this way will be used to support the Government’s efforts to help the homeless.
The surcharge, which is added to the current judicial stamp fee, including levels raised two years ago for the second property and properties purchased for rental purposes, could reach a value of 3%.
The Treasury expects this change to add up to <0xC2><0xA3>120 million a year.
About 13% of newly built properties in London are bought by non-residents in the UK, which leads to higher prices and makes it difficult for those who want to buy their first home.
Several prosperous areas of the country, especially the capital, have become "ghost cities" due to the high number of foreign buyers who spend a large part of their time outside the country.
The new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson called for a reduction in the judicial stamp duty to help young people buy their first home.
He accused big construction firms of keeping property prices high as a result of buying land without using it, and asked Theresa May to waive taxes on affordable homes in order to solve Britain’s “household problem.”
Corbyn has announced a number of attractive real estate reform proposals, including checks on rents and the cessation of unreasonable evictions.
It also wants to give the councils greater powers when it comes to building new houses.
Theresa May said: “Last year I said that I will dedicate my mandate as prime minister to fulfilling the British dream, a better life for every new generation.
And that means fixing the existing problems in the real estate market.
The UK will always be open to people who want to live, work and build a life here.
However, it is not fair for people who do not live in the UK, as well as companies with offices abroad, to be able to buy homes as easily as hard-working British residents.
For too many people, the dream of owning a home has become far too distant, and living in unworthy conditions is far too real.”
