Jack Ross, manager of the Sunderland football team, said that "his ultimate goal" is to become, at some point, the manager of the Scottish national team.
The 42-year-old Scotsman enjoys the challenge of "reviving" the northeastern club, which is currently ranked 3rd in the First League, with a three-point difference from first place.
He moved to the Stadium of Light team this summer after managing, last season, the return of the St. Mirren football team to the Scottish Premiership.
“I wanted to be a member of the national football team, but as a player.
We’ve made it to the national team’s B team and that’s about it,” Ross told Sportsound on BBC Scotland.
“But I’ve spent a lot of my childhood watching Scotland’s Hampden games with my father and I’ve always wanted to come back.
But I will only have this opportunity if I succeed as manager of the club.”
Ross' predecessors, as managers of Sunderland, include Dick Advocaat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio.
The former manager of Alloa Athletic said he has no emotions to be the successor to such established names and such a prominent club after refusing offers from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
“The only thing that worries me and that could affect my success is the question, ‘Can I help this team get back into the Premier League?’
There is no doubt that the structure and facilities of this club allow it to be in the Premier League,” he said.
“It’s not easy to get her to get there, but I think the only thing that would make me feel like a successful man is to contribute to the club’s return to the Premier League.”
Ross has only three years of leadership experience, after a stint as assistant manager at Dumbarton and another 15 months as a member of the training staff at Hearts.
He then helped Alloa recover after relegating to Division C and managed to save St. Mirren from relegation, helping the team win the championship title in the next season.
Ross said he feels better now than in his entire playing career at Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St. Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
“It was a decisive moment,” he said of the takeover of Alloa.
“I thought the role of manager was better for me than the role of player.
It may sound strange, because we had a good time, we won well and we had a few successful moments.
But it's hard to be a player.
You have to do a lot of things and repeat them every week.
I’m facing similar situations as a manager, in terms of stress and pressure, but I feel it’s the right role for me.
I’ve always wanted to be a manager and now that I can do that, I feel like it’s the thing that suits me best in my entire adult life.”
