Earthquakes and Tsunami in Indonesia
At least 384 people have died from a powerful earthquake and tsunami that hit Indonesia's Palu on Friday, authorities said, and the death toll is expected to rise.
Due to the disruption of communications networks, disaster authorities were unable to obtain any information from the Donggala Regency, an area north of Palu, which is closer to the epicentre of the earthquake with a magnitude of 7.5 on the Richter scale.
In Palu, more than 16,000 people were evacuated after the disaster.
Here are some key information about Palu and Donggala, from the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of the central province of Sulawesi Island, which lies at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of Sulawesi Island, with a population of about 379,800 in 2017.
The city celebrated 40 years of existence when it was hit by tsunami and earthquake.
Donggala is a regency that stretches on a coastline with an area of more than 300 km in the northwest of Sulawesi Island.
Regency, an administrative region that lies below a province, has a population of about 299,200 in 2017.
Fish farming and agriculture are the central focus of the economy of the central province of Sulawesi, especially the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel mining activities are also important in the province, but are mainly concentrated in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunamis several times over the past 100 years, according to Indonesia’s Disaster Management Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of houses in Donggala.
Also in 1996, a tsunami struck the western part of Donggala Regency, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the Pacific Circle of Fire, an area with intense seismic activity.
Here are some of the earthquakes and tsunamis that have occurred in recent years:
2004 – A powerful earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh in northern Sumatra triggered a tsunami that struck 14 countries, killing 226,000 people off the coast of the Indian Ocean, more than half of them from Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on the island of Nias off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake on the Richter scale struck the south of Indonesia's most populous island, Java, triggering a tsunami that struck the south coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A magnitude 7.6 earthquake on the Richter scale occurred near Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A magnitude 7.5 earthquake on the Richter scale struck one of the islands of Mentawai off the coast of Sumatra, triggering a tsunami up to 10 meters high that destroyed dozens of villages and killed around 300 people.
2016: A low-intensity earthquake occurred in the Pidie Jaya Regency of Aceh, causing damage and panic as people remembered the devastating 2004 earthquake and tsunami that resulted in a large number of deaths.
There was no tsunami this time, but more than 100 people died from the collapsed buildings.
2018: Several powerful earthquakes occurred on the tourist island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, most on the northern side of the island.
The earthquake destroyed thousands of buildings and thousands of tourists were temporarily stranded under rubble.
