How can the U.S.-China trade war benefit Beijing?
The salvos that heralded the start of the U.S.-China trade war have been deafening, and while there seems to be a long way to go until it is over, the two countries’ quarrels could be beneficial for Beijing in the long run, experts say.
U.S. President Donald Trump issued the first warning earlier this year by imposing tariffs on key imports from China, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The biggest escalation came this week with new tariffs hitting $200 billion worth of goods, effectively taxing half of all Chinese goods arriving in the United States.
Beijing has retaliated each time, most recently imposing a tax of between 5 and 10 percent on US goods worth $60 billion.
China has warned it will respond to every blow from the United States, and it is unlikely that the world’s second-largest economy will take a step back in the near future.
For Washington to withdraw, China must agree to its demands, but publicly giving in to the United States would be far too humiliating for Xi Jinping, the president of China.
However, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, U.S. pressure on the trade war could support China positively in the long run, reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a quick political decision taken in Washington or Beijing could lead to an economic collapse in both countries would actually be more dangerous than previously expected,” said Abigail Grace, an associate researcher who focuses on Asia at the Center for New American Security, a group of experts.
Syria ready for return of refugees, foreign minister says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help in rebuilding the country devastated by a war that has lasted for more than seven years.
During his speech at the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the situation in the country is improving.
“Today, conditions on the ground are more stable and secure, thanks to the progress made in combating terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate the areas destroyed by the terrorists so that things return to normal.
The existing conditions allow for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they have had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that targeted their daily lives and livelihoods.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the war broke out in 2011.
Six million people who continue to live in the country need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would be happy to receive help in rebuilding the devastated country.
But he stressed that conditional assistance or aid from countries sponsored by the insurgency would not be accepted.
