Red tide news: concentrations decreased in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Wildlife Protection Commission shows an overall decline in red tide concentrations for some areas of the Gulf of Tampa.
According to the Commission, uneven inflorescence conditions are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – suggesting lower concentrations.
This red tide inflorescence extends over a coastline of about 210 km from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
Spots can be found about 10 miles (16 km) off Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Average concentrations found in or off Pinellas County were reported last week, as well as low to high concentrations in Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations in Sarasota County, and background to high concentrations in and off Charlotte County.
Airway irritation continues to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
There have been no reports of airway irritation in northwest Florida in the past week.
